<Layout title="Module 8 – IV Therapy & Phlebotomy">
  <h1>Module 8: IV Therapy &amp; Phlebotomy</h1>
  <p>
    Intravenous therapy and blood specimen collection are essential nursing skills. They
    require strict aseptic technique, thorough assessment of access sites, and ongoing
    monitoring for complications.
  </p>

  <h2>Peripheral IV Access</h2>
  <h3>Site Selection</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Use the non-dominant arm whenever possible.</li>
    <li>Start distally; move proximally for subsequent attempts.</li>
    <li>Preferred sites: Forearm (cephalic, basilic, median cubital), back of hand (metacarpal veins).</li>
    <li>Avoid: Antecubital fossa (limits mobility), sites of infection/phlebitis/infiltration, extremity with AV fistula, post-mastectomy side, or arm with lymphedema.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Catheter Selection</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Gauge</th><th>Color</th><th>Use</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>14–16 G</td><td>Orange / Grey</td><td>Rapid fluid resuscitation, blood products (large bore)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>18 G</td><td>Green</td><td>Blood products, viscous medications</td></tr>
      <tr><td>20 G</td><td>Pink/Rose</td><td>Most adult IV medications; blood draws</td></tr>
      <tr><td>22–24 G</td><td>Blue / Yellow</td><td>Pediatric patients, fragile veins, elderly</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Remember</strong>
    Gauge is inversely proportional to size — a smaller gauge number means a larger catheter
    lumen and faster flow rate.
  </div>

  <h2>IV Insertion Procedure</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Verify order; gather supplies; perform hand hygiene; don gloves.</li>
    <li>Apply tourniquet 4–6 inches above insertion site; identify vein.</li>
    <li>Cleanse site with chlorhexidine (preferred) or alcohol swab; allow to dry completely.</li>
    <li>Anchor vein; insert catheter at 10–30° angle, bevel up; advance until flashback of blood appears.</li>
    <li>Lower angle; advance catheter off stylet; remove stylet.</li>
    <li>Release tourniquet; apply extension set / cap; flush with normal saline (2–5 mL).</li>
    <li>Secure catheter; apply transparent semipermeable membrane (TSM) dressing; label with date, time, gauge, and initials.</li>
    <li>Dispose of sharps immediately in sharps container.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>IV Fluid Therapy</h2>
  <h3>IV Fluid Tonicity</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Examples</th><th>Effect</th><th>Clinical Use</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Isotonic</strong></td>
        <td>0.9% NaCl (NS), LR, D5W (in bag — isotonic; acts hypotonic once metabolized)</td>
        <td>Expands intravascular volume; no net fluid shift</td>
        <td>Volume replacement, surgical patients, shock</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Hypotonic</strong></td>
        <td>0.45% NaCl (½ NS), 0.33% NaCl</td>
        <td>Fluid shifts into cells — hydrates intracellular compartment</td>
        <td>Cellular dehydration, DKA (after initial resuscitation)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Hypertonic</strong></td>
        <td>3% NaCl, D10W, D5NS, D5LR</td>
        <td>Draws fluid out of cells into vasculature</td>
        <td>Severe hyponatremia, cerebral edema</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>IV Flow Rate Calculation</h3>
  <p><strong>mL/hr = Total Volume (mL) ÷ Time (hr)</strong></p>
  <p><strong>gtt/min = (Volume mL × Drop factor) ÷ Time in minutes</strong></p>
  <p>
    <em>Example:</em> Infuse 1000 mL NS over 8 hours using tubing with a drop factor of
    15 gtt/mL.<br />
    gtt/min = (1000 × 15) ÷ 480 = 31.25 ≈ 31 gtt/min
  </p>

  <h2>IV Complications</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Complication</th><th>Signs &amp; Symptoms</th><th>Nursing Action</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Infiltration</td>
        <td>Swelling, coolness, pallor, slowed infusion</td>
        <td>Stop infusion; remove catheter; elevate extremity; apply warm/cold compress per policy</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Extravasation</td>
        <td>Infiltration of vesicant drug; tissue damage, blistering</td>
        <td>Stop immediately; do not remove catheter (may need antidote instillation); notify provider; follow facility extravasation protocol</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Phlebitis</td>
        <td>Redness, warmth, swelling, tenderness along vein, palpable cord</td>
        <td>Discontinue IV; rotate to new site; apply warm compress</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Infection / Sepsis</td>
        <td>Purulent drainage, fever, systemic signs</td>
        <td>Remove catheter; culture site; notify provider; blood cultures if systemic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Air embolism</td>
        <td>Sudden dyspnea, chest pain, hypotension, "mill wheel" murmur</td>
        <td>Position left lateral Trendelenburg; O₂; notify provider STAT</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Fluid overload</td>
        <td>Dyspnea, crackles, edema, hypertension, bounding pulse</td>
        <td>Slow or stop infusion; elevate HOB; notify provider; administer diuretics as ordered</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>IV Site Maintenance</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Assess site at the beginning of every shift and before each infusion.</li>
    <li>Change peripheral IV site every 72–96 hours (or per facility policy); change if signs of complication develop.</li>
    <li>Change IV tubing every 72–96 hours for standard infusions; every 24 hours for lipids and blood.</li>
    <li>Flush with saline before and after each medication; use SASH (Saline–Administer–Saline–Heparin) for heparin-lock lines per facility policy.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Phlebotomy (Blood Specimen Collection)</h2>
  <h3>Order of Draw</h3>
  <p>Using the correct order prevents contamination of tube additives:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Blood cultures (yellow / sterile)</li>
    <li>Coagulation tubes (light blue — sodium citrate)</li>
    <li>Serum separator / SST (gold / red-grey tiger top)</li>
    <li>Heparin tubes (green)</li>
    <li>EDTA / CBC tubes (lavender / purple)</li>
    <li>Oxalate / fluoride tubes (grey — glucose, lactate)</li>
  </ol>
  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Mnemonic: "Stop Light, Got Big Lavender Grapes"</strong>
    Sterile, Light blue, Gold, Blue/Heparin, Lavender, Grey
  </div>

  <h3>Venipuncture Procedure</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Verify order; label tubes at bedside before drawing (use 2 patient identifiers).</li>
    <li>Perform hand hygiene; apply tourniquet; select site; cleanse with antiseptic; allow to dry.</li>
    <li>Insert needle bevel up at 15–30° angle; anchor vein; advance tube(s) following order of draw.</li>
    <li>Release tourniquet before removing needle; apply pressure 2–3 minutes; apply bandage.</li>
    <li>Gently invert tubes 5–10 times to mix additives; transport per facility lab requirements.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Infiltration:</strong> Inadvertent administration of non-vesicant IV fluid into surrounding tissue.</li>
    <li><strong>Extravasation:</strong> Infiltration of a vesicant (tissue-damaging) medication.</li>
    <li><strong>Phlebitis:</strong> Inflammation of a vein, often from IV catheter irritation.</li>
    <li><strong>Vesicant:</strong> Medication capable of causing tissue necrosis if extravasation occurs (e.g., dopamine, calcium chloride, many chemotherapy agents).</li>
    <li><strong>Tonicity:</strong> Osmotic concentration of a solution relative to body fluids.</li>
    <li><strong>Order of draw:</strong> Standardized sequence for filling blood tubes to prevent additive cross-contamination.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
